Graphical abstract The preparation of the catalyst is shown in the above figure. As is shown above, a novel nanofiber was designed and synthesized with glucose and PAN by electrospinning, which was employed as a platform and reductant. Then a certain amount of ammonia water was added drop wise to the copper nitrate solution to form copper ammonia complex ion ([Cu(NH3)4]2+), and the [Cu(NH3)4]2+ was attracted to the nanofibers and was simultaneously reduced by glucose on the fibers. Glucose was dispersed in polyacrylonitrile (PAN) nanofibers to develop a novel supporter for reducing and anchoring Cu0 by hydrothermal process. The newly developed catalyst was characterized by transmission electron microscopy (TEM), X-ray diffraction (XRD) and X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS), and amorphous Cu0 were obtained. The prepared Cu0 nanocatalyst was investigated as a heterogeneous catalyst for N-arylation reaction of N-heterocyclic compounds and a wide range of aryl iodides including iodobenzene, electron-rich and electron-poor aryl iodides, which performed excellent catalytic activity. Keywords Cu-based catalyst Nanofibers Catalyst N-arylation reaction 1 Introduction The applications of copper (Cu) and Cu-based nanoparticles (NPs) have attracted extensive attention in the field of heterogeneous organic catalysis in recent years [1]. A lot of methods, such as chemical reduction [2,3], microwave treatment [4] and thermal reduction metal vapor [5], have been used to synthesize Cu NPs with different sizes and shapes, which give rise to excellent properties. Among these methods, chemical reduction methods are most widely used for the synthesis of copper NPs, because it is easy to control the shape and size of Cu NPs by varying the copper salts, solvents, reducing agents, reduction temperature, concentrations and other parameters. Despite continual attempts, there are still new types of catalytic conversion route that have not been explored. Arylated N-heterocyclic compounds constitute an important kind of compounds due to their widely applications in pharmaceutical, biologically and functional materials [6–9]. Commonly, constructing these heterocyclic compounds involves cross-coupling reactions through nucleophilic substitution of aryl halides. This method, as a matter of fact, requires high reaction temperatre, strong bases, stoichiometric use of catalyst and result in low yields [10]. Palladium-catalyzed CN coupling methods are widely used as excellent means for N-arylation reaction [11,12]. However, the palladium catalytic still has quite a few limitations, such as high Pd loadings, long reaction times and amine derivatives of heterocycles [13]. Compared with palladium catalyst, Cu-catalyzed N-arylation reactions have been receiving more attention due to their low price and excellent properties [14–17]. Researchers have been made great efforts in Cu-catalyzed N-arylation reactions and obtained some achievements. For example, Animesh’s group reported copper2+ catalyst for CN cross coupling between aryl halides and aliphatic diamines [18]; Zhu and co-workers reported Copper-Catalysed Ullmann CN coupling reaction in Water [19]; Zhang and co-workers developed a CuI/metformin catalyst for the CN coupling reaction [20]; Patel’ group reported the synthesis of 2,3-disubstituted quinazolinones through sequential N-arylation and oxidative CH amidation with CuO nanoparticle [21]. Among all these copper-based catalyst, nulvalent copper catalysts have attracted more and more researchers' attention. However, in the modern era of organic synthesis, reduced copper catalysts were easily oxidized and it is difficult to separate catalyst and product from homogeneous systems. In many cases, in order to solve these problems, metal catalyst are usually anchored on various supporters, such as carbon nanotube [22,23], polymer [24–26], metallic oxide [27] zeolites [28,29], oxidized grapheme [30], microspheres [31] and glycosyl compounds [32,33]. Among all these supporters, nanofibers have been one of the most progressive research areas due to their one-dimensional properties, large specific surface area and mechanical strength. It has been reported that PAN fibers supported Cu catalyst through ion exchange method and nternal doping method in our work [34,35]. However, all these methods were made the reducing agent to attack metal ions so that the metal was easily agglomerate. In this work, a new method was developed (Fig. 1 ), allowing glucose to dop into PAN nanofibers by electrospinning technology, and the prepared glucose/PAN composite fibers were served as the platforms to immobilize Cu2+ on their surface. Simultaneously, the Cu2+ was reduced by glucose through hydrothermal process as previously reported [36]. Then the prepared catalyst was used in N-arylation reaction and showed higher catalytic activity and excellent selectivity. 2 Experimental 2.1 synthesis of Cu/NFs catalyst All chemicals were purchased from commercial suppliers and used as received. PAN (1.6g) was dispersed in DMF solution (18.4g) by stirring at room temperature for 12h. Then, glucose (2.0g) was added into the above dispersion. And the substance ratio of PAN and glucose was 2.7:1. The resulted mixture was still stirred at room temperature for about 12h. The glucose/PAN fibers were fabricated through electrospinning technology. Then the glucose/PAN fibers were solidified at 120°C for about 5h. Cu(NO3)2·3H2O (0.016g) was dissolved in 50ml distilled water and then ammonium water (25%) was dropwise added into the copper nitrate solution, leading to a color change from transparent to dark blue. After 10min, 0.1g glucose/PAN fibers was soaked into this solution, which was transferred to the reactor and heated at 120°C for about 9h. Then, the reactor was cooled down to room temperature. The red fibers was washed with distilled water three times followed by washing with ethanol, and dried in a vacuum drying oven to get Cu/NFs catalyst. 2.2 Characterization The morphologies and structures of the as-fabricated samples were observed by scanning electron microscopy (SEM, Hitachi S-3400N, Japan). The phase and crystalline structures of the as-prepared samples were characterized by X-ray diffraction (XRD, Rigaku Ultima IV, Japan) over a range of 2θ angles from 5° to 90° with a scanning rate of 3°/min. The characteristic functional groups in different samples were recorded by Fourier transform infrared spectra (FTIR, Nicolet Nexus 670 spectrophotometer). X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS, Escalab 250xi, ThermoFisher Scientific, USA) measurements were performed to examine the chemical composition of Cu/NFs catalyst. Gas chromatography (GC, GC-2010, Shimadzu, Japan) and Mass spectrometry (MS, Austin, TX 78728, USA) results were performed to confirm the reaction products. 2.3 Catalytic reaction The catalyst activities of Cu/NFs directing arylation reactions of N-heterocyclic compounds and iodobenzene were explored. In a typical process, a mixture of aryl-halide (0.25mmol), N-heterocyclic compound (0.75mmol), Cs2CO3 (0.5mmol) and Cu/NFs (50mg) in 5ml DMF were placed in a glass reaction tube. Then the solution was heated at 140°C for 14h. Next, the mixture was cooled down to room temperature and diluted with DMF. The catalyst was washed with distilled water and ethanol. The ingredients of reaction products were confirmed and measured by GC–MS, and the results were shown in the supporting information. 3 Results and discussion The Fourier transform infrared spectra (FTIR) were used to demonstrate the characteristic groups in the samples (Fig. 2 ). Fig. 2a shows the well-known molecular absorption peaks of PAN [37–41] around 2934.3cm−1 and 2866.4cm−1 (corresponding to CH stretching), 2244.0cm−1 (corresponding to CN stretching), 1453.2cm−1 (corresponding to CH blending) and 1729.9cm−1 (corresponding to CO stretching). For comparison, the peak at 1083.4cm−1 in spectrum 2b and 2c is corresponded to CO stretching vibrations [42]. Besides, the peaks around 3293.7cm−1, 1151.1cm−1 and 1035.9cm−1 in spectrum 2c are corresponded to OH stretching vibration [43], illustrating that glucose were doping into the fibers. The XPS pattern was carried out to affirm the composition and chemical state of Cu/NFs catalysts (Fig. 3 ). The major contribution of the Cu 2p3/2 peak (932.6eV) and 2p1/2 peak (952.4eV) were observed, indicating that Cu possess the oxidation state (0) on the supports [44]. And XPS revealed that Cu was doped into the Cu/NFs, with ∼12.27% Cu detected in the sample. The wide-angle XRD pattern for as-prepared Cu/NFs catalysts was displayed in Fig. 4 . No obvious diffraction peaks of Cu faces are observed, illustrating that the Cu species is highly dispersed in nanofibers. SEM images were taken to observe the morphology of the samples. As shown in Fig. 5 , the diameter of the fibers ranges from 250nm to 300nm, the high-temperature solidifications and hydrothermal process have no influence on the morphology of the nanofibers. The EDS picture (Fig. 5c inset) demonstrates that Cu was anchored on the nanofibers. Fig. 6 shows typical transmission election microscopy (TEM) image of the synthesized Cu/NFs catalyst, in which no Cu NPs were developed from the nanofibers. The distribution of different elements in Cu/NFs composites were clarified by STEM-HADDP (Fig. 7 ), which illustrate that Cu were densely distributed on the PAN nanofibers. From what has been discussed above, it could be confirmed that copper, which exist with amorphous state, was homogeneous and evenly distributed on the PAN nanofibers. To optimize the reaction conditions, a set of experiments between pyrrole(0.75mmol) and iodobenzene (0.5mmol) were taken as a model reaction (Table 1 ). The effect of different solvents were examined in reaction system (Table 1 entries 1–5). After testing five different solvents (DMF, DMAC, NMP, DMSO and Toluene), DMF gave the best results and both conversion and selectivity were achieved 99.99%. When the reaction time was shortened to 4h and 8h, the products were observed only 35.85% and 64.54% yields (Table 1 entries 6 and 7). The amount of catalyst was also examined. From entries 1 and 8-9 (Table 1), when the amount of catalyst was decreased from 0.05g to 0.03g and 0.01g, iodobenzene conversion were also decreased. The reaction temperature also played an important role in this reaction. When the reaction temperature was decreased, the products’ yield and selectivity were also decreased gradually (Table 1 entries 10 and 11). Besides, the reaction with K2CO3 as the base had only 3.67% yields of the products (Table 1 entry 12). No product conversion was observed when nanofibers were used as the catalyst in the reaction (Table 1 entry 13), indicating that the copper component was the only catalytically active site responsible to the catalytic reaction. And we compared the results achieved in this work with those reported previously for the catalysis of N-arylation (Table 1 entries 14–16). The catalyst in this work played better catalytic properties than other previously reported catalysts. Subsequently, in order to explore the general applicability of this reaction system, the scope of N-heterocyclic compounds (pyrrole, pyrazol and imidazole) with various iodobenzene was examined under the standard reaction conditions (Table 2 ). As expecting, iodobenzene as substrate reacted with N-heterocyclic compounds all had 99.99% yields and excellent selectivity (Table 2 entrise 1–3). However, substituents on iodobenzene would display significant impacts on the reaction efficiency [48]. Hence, different substituents of iodobenzene reacted with N-heterocyclic compounds were tested. In the standard reaction system, the iodobenzene with electron-donating functional group (-OCH3) coupled with pyrrole, pyrazol and imidazole successfully with great yields and selectivity even the iodobenzene had ortho substituent (Table 2 entries 4–12). When the electron-withdrawing groups in the para position and meta position of iodobenzene reacted with pyrrole, pyrazol and imidazole still had higher yields (Table 2 entries 13–18), but the ortho-substituted 2-nitroiodobenzene had a little lower yield probably due to the influence of steric hindrance (Table 2 entries 19–21). This may be the result of a combination of electron density and steric hindrance. The reusability of Cu/NFs catalyst was examined by the N-arylation reaction of iodobenzene with pyrrole (Table 3 ). The Cu/NFs catalyst could be effectively recycled and reused up to five consecutive catalytic cycles, but an obvious decrease in the product yield was observed at the 5th cycle. This possibly attribute to the copper leaching from the nanofibers. 4 Conclusion In conclusion, a novel nanofibers was designed and synthesized with glucose and PAN by electrospinning, which was employed as a platform and reductant. Then the Cu0 was deposited on the nanofibers to form the heterogeneous nanocatalyst (Cu/NFs). Cu0 was evenly dispersed on the nanofibers through this easy and efficient approach. The glucose doped in the nanofibers was demonstrated by employing FTIR diagram. Deposited Cu0 with amorphous state was determined by XRD, TEM, STEM-HADDP and XPS. This heterogeneous Cu/NFs catalyst showed excellent catalytic activity and reusability in the N-arylation reaction under optimized conditions, and further investigation of this catalyst to other chemical transformations is underway in our laboratory.
